councilMember.bio: Tina FitzGerald, MHA, MS, MLS (ASCP)cm, CPC is the Director of Laboratory Services at Anna Jaques Hospital, Newburyport MA,  a position she has held since May 2015. Ms. FitzGerald oversees the daily operations of the laboratory while ensuring departmental compliance with all regulatory agencies, personnel management, growth through relationship building, marketing and sales, selection, evaluation and implementation of laboratory instruments, and quality improvement and IT initiatives. Previously, Ms. FitzGerald was Lab Operations Manager for Holy Family Hospital at Merrimack Valley and Methuen and Laboratory Administrative Director for Merrimack Valley Hospital. As past Director of Physician Relations & Services at Women & Infants Hospital of Rhode Island,  Ms. FitzGerald oversaw a large physician outreach program which allowed for expansion of hospital services to community physicians and institutions. Ms. FitzGerald's specialties include medical staff relations, especially in regards to communication, negotiation, and facilitation, business development and sales, financial management and clinical support services, HIPAA, coding, and business analysis. She received a MHA from Suffolk University, Boston MA, a MS in Biotechnology and Management, a BS in Microbiology and a BS in Medical Technology from Salve Regina University. Ms. FitzGerald is also a Certified Professional Coder through the American Academy of Professional Coders. She is a member of various Laboratory and Management Associations. Ms. FitzGerald is also serving as a Lab Director at College of American Pathologist.

Michael Hickton had been the Laboratory Manager of the Blood Sciences Department, Portsmouth Pathology Service at Queen Alexandra Hospital, United Kingdom since 1991. councilMember.bio: Michael Thomas, MA, MB, FRCP, DTM&H, is Clinical Director at The Blood Care Foundation, United Kingdom, where he is also a member of the Executive Committee which manages the Foundation, in addition to being one of the four Trustees on the Management Board. The Foundation provides emergency transfusion cover to people who require blood and are in a country where blood is either unavailable or the local screening techniques are inadequate, one of Dr. Thomas' manifold responsibilities include ensuring that the blood which is supplied is only drawn from an internationally recognised blood bank and that the method of transport and storage ensures the blood will be in prime condition when transfused to the patient; and ensuring there is consultant advice on transfusion medicine problems available 24/7. Dr. Thomas is a clinical hematologist and tropical medicine specialist. He has experience in leading research groups into blood substitutes and has founded the British Autologous Blood Transfusion Society. In addition to his role with the Foundation, Dr. Thomas is also an independent consultant on transfusion practice in Disaster and Emergency Medicine, a topic on which he has published over 30 papers and given over 50 major international lectures.  Dr. Thomas has worked with a number of multi-national companies on the production and trialling of cell free oxygen carrying resuscitation fluids (CFOCRFs), commonly called artificial blood.  Prior to his retirement from the Royal Army Medical Corps in the rank of Colonel, he was the Director of the Army Blood Transfusion Service in which he had to transport blood to British Service Hospitals worldwide as well as providing the blood cover for the Falklands campaign, the Gulf War and the military time in the Balkans.

councilMember.bio: Leonard Levin, MS, MBA, is the Administrative Laboratory Director at Holy Redeemer Hospital in Meadowbrook, PA. He has over 30 years of work experience in various capacities related to clinical laboratory sciences, including laboratory testing in clinical microbiology and serology, scientific writing of articles focusing on diagnosis, treatment, and epidemiology of HIV and AIDS, and management of clinical laboratories for urban as well as suburban hospitals.  Currently, in addition to hospital laboratory management, Len serves as a reviewer and writer of online continuing education modules for Gannett Healthcare. Len has been quoted in various clinical laboratory professional publications, including CAP Today, Laboratory Medicine, Advance for Medical Laboratory Professionals, and Medical Laboratory Observer (MLO).  He was also profiled recently in Ostomy Wound Management magazine, in which he highlighted the contributions of the clinical laboratory to the care of wound patients.
councilMember.hightlights: Leonard has over 30 years of experience in the clinical lab (lab testing, clinical microbiology, serology, etc.). He let me know that, currently, his lab utilizes Ortho blood bank and gel technology products and that, in the past, when working at other hospitals, he utilized clinical chemistry analyzers "for many years" in addition to Ortho's blood bank products. Importantly, he noted the following regarding the Vitros system: "I have directed laboratories utilizing Ortho Vitros 5600 chemistry/immunoassay analyzers. I am aware of the Vitros ECi immunodiagnostic system, the technology of which was incorporated into the immunoassay side of the Vitros 5600 system."
